			<h3 ><a href="#p1685325">Re: Car Insurance Advice</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=1685325&amp;sid=dbd612b095921ececc91042871a29805#p1685325"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1901&amp;sid=dbd612b095921ececc91042871a29805">Quasimodo</a></strong> &raquo; Fri May 03, 2013 3:45 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content">Yes, my understanding is that the rule of thumb is a per year premium comparison to the value of the car. <br /><br />Because comprehensive looks really inexpensive, and provides coverage for just about everything but collision (vandalism, theft, flood, fire among other perils), I'd be inclined to keep that coverage even if you decide to drop collision.<br /><br />John</div>

			<div id="sig1685325" class="signature">Many wealthy people are little more than janitors of their possessions. <br /><br />Frank Lloyd Wright, architect (1867-1959)</div>

		</div>

		
