	<div id="p1685387" class="post bg1">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p1685387">Re: Car Insurance Advice</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=1685387&amp;sid=dbd612b095921ececc91042871a29805#p1685387"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=434&amp;sid=dbd612b095921ececc91042871a29805">jeffyscott</a></strong> &raquo; Fri May 03, 2013 4:38 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content">I think that &quot;rule&quot; is used by insurance agents in order to encourage over-insuring. Who totals their car once per decade? Also why would it be the market value rather than the amount you could collect? If you have $1000 deductible and the market value of your car is $1000, would you pay $100 per year for this coverage?<br /><br />Assuming the car is worth $4500, with $1000 deductible the most you would collect from a collision would be $3500 and you are paying $354. While this does, perhaps, thus exceed a modified rule of thumb <img src="./images/smilies/icon_question.gif" alt=":?:" title="Question" /> , in any case this seems to me like too much to pay to avoid a small (at least to me) potential loss of $3500. <br /><br />The decision should be more based on the impact of a ~$3500 loss, if that would be a minor financial blip then it is not worth insuring against, if it would ruin your life then it may be.</div>

			<div id="sig1685387" class="signature"><span style="font-style: italic">press on, regardless</span> - John C. Bogle</div>

		</div>

		
